e>Tom</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Widger</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI015493%2F1"><gtr:id>81F1EB24-9822-4BCD-93A2-441E402B34D8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Suicidal behaviour in a globalising context: exploring changing causalites and moralities of self-harm in Sri Lanka and comparative settings</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I015493/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Suicidal behaviour has been a significant health and social problem in Sri Lanka for several decades. Dr Widger's PDF will explore the connotations of modelling suicidal behaviour in Sri Lanka as a socially powerful act with ramifications that spiral much further than survival or death. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Widger posits that suicide attempts, acts of deliberate self-harm and the self-inflicted death can be understood as a 'denial of sociality' in which actors structurally constrained in their actions can forcefully and often legitimately question and challenge social status relationships within families and communities. In so doing, Widger suggests that through self-harm individuals accomplish what he calls an expos&amp;eacute; of the 'evitability of the inevitable'. By committing fatal self-harm, people voluntarily remove themselves from the world of significant others (relationships that are assumed to be 'inevitable', such as those defined by kinship) and thus question the sociality that binds them together: sociality that for most of the time is taken for granted. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Non-fatal suicide attempts and suicide threats are powerful for the same reason. Although death is avoided, and in some cases never stands as a serious threat, the association of the behaviour with permanent separation from others with whom attachment is assumed to be given is still very much part of the eventual outcome. It could be said that all kinds of suicidal behaviour&amp;nbsp;- both lethal and non-lethal&amp;nbsp;- function to put the idea separation into other people's minds, as a fundamental part of a broader communicative strategy. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>69515</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Article on The Lancet Global Health blog</gtr:description><gtr:form>A magazine, newsletter or online publication</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>93F2334B-77CA-4EE0-91CD-12FEE320105A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>None</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545686fd398278.15640445</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other academic audiences (collaborators, peers etc.)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://globalhealth.thelancet.com/2014/06/27/cultural-social-and-medical-equity-could-provide-lasting-solutions-sri-lankas-suicide</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Suicide conference</gtr:description><gtr:form>Scientific meeting (conference/symposium etc.)</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>430B6EF4-FB04-478F-B413-721B5D245876</gtr:id><g